== Descriptor Feature: Test Suite Context ==

-- Feature Summary --

The "descriptor" feature adds a one-to-one class relationship:
  class D describes A { }   // D is the descriptor class for A
  class A descriptor D { }  // A declares D as its descriptor

Rules:
- The relationship is bidirectional and must be declared on BOTH sides
- One-to-one: D can describe exactly one class; A can have at most one descriptor
- Hierarchy: if B extends A (and A has descriptor DA), B must also declare a
  descriptor DB. DB must be a subtype of DA (not necessarily direct), and DB
  must declare "describes B". DB can be an indirect subtype via intermediate
  classes that don't declare "describes".
- All subclasses of a described class must also declare a descriptor.
- A descriptor subclass that does NOT declare "describes" is valid — it is just
  a plain subclass of the descriptor and describes nothing.
- Polymorphic: class A<T> descriptor DA<T> { } is supported. Type parameter
  substitution is checked: DA<T>.describes must equal A<T> after substitution.
- Constructor: the descriptor instance is the implicit first argument to A.new:
    def d = D.new(); def a = A.new(d);    // or A.new(d, other_args)
- Field access: a.descriptor returns the descriptor instance; its type is the
  declared descriptor type. The field is READ-ONLY (assignment is AssignError).
- Subtype assignment: def d: DA = b.descriptor (b: B, DB extends DA) is valid.
- The -descriptors flag must be passed to v3c to enable the feature.

Error types used in seman tests:
  DescriptorError  - hierarchy/correspondence violations
  TypeError        - type mismatch in assignments or constructor calls
  AssignError      - attempt to assign to the read-only .descriptor field
  UnresolvedMember - .descriptor accessed on a non-class or class without descriptor

-- Dynamic Tests to Generate (in test/descriptor/*.v3) --

Dynamic tests use //@execute = N (expected return value) or
//@execute = !SomeException (expected exception).

Inheritance at runtime:
  - B extends A; access b.descriptor as DB and as DA (upcast)
  - Override descriptor in subclass; verify each class returns its own descriptor type
  - Deep hierarchy (3+ levels): verify each level has the right descriptor

Descriptor as factory / reflective use:
  - Store an array of descriptor instances; use them to construct objects
  - Descriptor holds type-specific behavior; call a method on .descriptor
  - Compare two descriptors for equality (same descriptor shared across instances)

Exact-type dynamic check:
  - Downcast: (b as B).descriptor should have type DB at runtime
  - Type test: b is B should still work with descriptor present
  - Incorrect cast involving descriptor hierarchy

class D describes C {
  // def descriptor: DD; #compiler-runtime
  // ---- added by compiler
  // hidden def typeid: int;
  // hidden var refmap: int;     0 == unset, != 0 set
  // hidden var size: int;       size including prefix fields
}

class C descriptor D {
  // def descriptor: D; #compiler-runtime
}

Observations:
 - Would be helpful if compiler knows which descriptors get extensions during reachability
 - CiRuntime.scanObject has untyped pointers, needs to use machine-level accesses, can't use descriptor.field
   - all descriptor.typeid, descriptor.refmap, and descriptor.size fields need to be at the same offset for each descriptor type
 
Questions:
 - CiRuntime.setDescriptorExtension versus RiRuntime.setDescriptorExtension
   - CiRuntime allows the compiler to implement it
 - CiRuntime.setDescriptorExtension(Range<bool>) or CiRuntime.setDescriptorExtension(refmap)?
 - How to get the existing typeid / refmap for a type?
   - Can use descriptor.typeid and index into CiRuntime.GC_TYPE_TABLE
 - Reachability is going to eliminate unused descriptors
 - RiGc will compute object size, but allocation sequence emitted by compiler needs size
 - Header encoding
   - could use 00 and > maximum typeid; would work on 32-bit but won't work if descriptor is too well aligned on 64 bit
     0x0000_0004_0000_0000 would trick it
   - 0bpppppppp_ppppp000 => pointer to descriptor object
   - 0btttttttt_tttttt01 => regular object, t = type id; requires either shift or mtable / range check adjustment for extra + 1
   - 0b00000000_00000010 => primitive array
   - 0brrrrrrrr_rrrrrr11 => mixed array, r = refmap != 0, special-case scanning for refmap = 1
 - How to communicate offsets to runtime system?
 - What about extensions with more than ~30 fields?
 - Is messing with the typeid ever really necessary
 - What about a general CiRuntime.typeId<T>() method to get the type id of T?

CiRuntime.FEATURE_DESCRIPTOR_HEADERS - if true, enables new header encoding

CiRuntime.FEATURE_DESCRIPTOR_EXTENSIONS - if true, then a descriptor might have an extension and a size


-- Option 1: language-provided fields ---
descriptor.typeid
descriptor.refmap
descriptor.size
// which also allows
Pointer.atField(descriptor.typeid)
Pointer.atField(descriptor.refmap)
Pointer.atField(descriptor.size)

- Advantages:
  - nicer syntax
  - easy to detect which descriptors have extensions in reachability analysis
  - works more like regular fields
- Disadvatnages:
  - these are really target-specific fields (then again, Pointer and Pointer.atObject are target-specific)
  - runtime cannot actually use a generic .typeid or .refmap, needs to use Pointer.atField anyway


-- Option 2: runtime offset constants ---
CiRuntime.DESCRIPTOR_REFMAP_OFFSET
CiRuntime.DESCRIPTOR_SIZE_OFFSET
CiRuntime.DESCRIPTOR_TYPEID_OFFSET

- Advantages:
  - no new operators
- Disadvantages:
  - no way to tell in reachability which types it's used for
  - unlike other mechanisms in use currently (E.g. Pointer.atField)

-- Option 3: Pointer.at* operators ---
Pointer.atDescriptorTypeId(descriptor)
Pointer.atDescriptorRefMap(descriptor)
Pointer.atDescriptorSize(descriptor)

- Advantages:
  - only have new operators on pointers
  - easy to detect which descriptors have extensions in reachability analysis
- Disadvantages:
  - ugly syntax
  - spreads more runtime stuff into Pointer (but Pointer.atLength, Pointer.atEnd, etc)
  - still need to compute offset for RiGc.scanObject

-- Option 4: no operators, just use raw offsets ---
RiRuntime just relies on ABI knowledge, same as headers.
var descOop = oop.load<Pointer>();
var typeid = (descOop + CiRuntime.REF_SIZE).load<int>();
var refmap = (descOop + CiRuntime.REF_SIZE + 4).load<int>();
var size = (descOop + CiRuntime.REF_SIZE + 8).load<int>();

- Advantages: no additional CiRuntime members

- Question: what is the CiRuntime contract?
CiRuntime.setDescriptorExtension
        (refs: Range<bool>)             // Compiler emits code to compute refmap, size
        (refmap: int)                   // Caller must compute refmap, compiler computes size; caller needs CiRuntime.refmapOf<T>() or RiRuntime help
        (refmap: int, size: int)        // Caller must compute refmap and size; caller needs CiRuntime.refmapOf<T>()
       